{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497071"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:03:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1467"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1467"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.08,0.81,0.02,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85458"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"765"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10360"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36280"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man is retrieved from the scene of a motor car accident, in which he was the driver involved in a head-on collision. He is fully conscious, alert and orientated and complaining of abdominal pain. He has an unremarkable medical history and does not use any medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 98/72 mmHg, pulse rate 100/min, respiratory rate 18/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2 \u003C/sub\u003E98% on room air. There is guarding and tenderness in the right hypochondrium. Two large bore intravenous cannulae are inserted and his blood pressure improves to 110/74 mmHg after 2L of fluid resuscitation. A FAST scan is positive for fluid in the peritoneum and a CT scan is performed (Image). Throughout the scan, the patient complains of a tender abdomen. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the scan, the patient becomes unconscious. His blood pressure is 85/55 mmHg and pulse rate 130/min. Despite resuscitation with blood products, the patient\u0027s blood pressure and pulse rate fail to improve. Urgent discussion with interventional radiology does not identify a clear artery to embolise.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continued observation with fluid resuscitation","Laparoscopic drainage","Laparotomy","Diagnostic peritoneal aspiration","Angiography/embolisation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT shows that there is a large liver laceration involving the posterior aspect of the liver with surrounding haematoma and free fluid. The patient losing consciousness, complaining of tender abdomen and being persistently hypotensive indicates ongoing bleeding that needs urgent intervention. As there is no clear arterial bleed that can be embolised and the patient is haemodynamically unstable, an emergency \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the justified next step in management to control the haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinued observation with fluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect given that the patient has lost consciousness and is persistently hypotensive despite resuscitation. This is a sign of ongoing bleeding or another serious pathology in the abdomen that is unable to be managed by conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in such situations as it will not resolve the underlying cause of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic peritoneal lavage/aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E was once a common diagnostic tool for evaluating intra-abdominal injuries, but it has largely been replaced by more sensitive imaging techniques such as computed tomography (CT) scans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngiography/embolisation\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for patients with localised liver trauma with a clearly visible arterial bleeder and who are haemodynamically stable however in this case there is no identified artery to embolism so this is not an appropriate course of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Liver trauma in a persistent haemodynamically unstable patient requires emergency laparotomy."],"references":["Coccolini F, Coimbra R, Ordonez C, et al. Liver trauma: WSES 2020 guidelines. World J Emerg Surg. 2020;15:24\u201349. Available from: https://wjes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13017-020-00302-5","Trauma Victoria. Abdominal Trauma [Internet]. Updated 2023 Oct 5 [cited 2025 May 18]. Available from: https://trauma.reach.vic.gov.au/guidelines/abdominal-trauma/key-messages"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85458"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1467"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19818"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19818"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/de38bb57-f923-420c-be27-83be613fe985.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/de38bb57-f923-420c-be27-83be613fe985.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":674,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85458","links":{"sel